description:
We are in 2018 and a-synchronousness is an unescapable part of most applications. Wether you work on back-end code, a mobile application or a website, chances are you are confronted on a daily basis by the challenges of asynchronous programming, including its most common pitfalls such as callback-hell or classes implementing a dozen interfaces.

Several approaches have been proposed by the industry to solve those issues, and among them Reactive programming seem to be getting quite a lot of traction. So what is it? Basically it's an API that relies on a sophisticated version of the Observer pattern along with functional programming techniques to provide the primitives that enable developers to compose, transform and consume asynchronous event. The nice part is that the Rx project has designed a common API for this purpose, which is then declined in several similar-looking implementation for the most common languages, such as Java, JavaScript, Swift, Kotlin, etc.

Through Reactive programming developers are enabled to streamline and improve the readability of their asynchronous code. For instance, consider this snippet that leverages RxSwift to listen to a search input, perform a network request, and transform its result to a UI element:

searchBar.rx.text.orEmpty
    .flatMapLatest { query -> Observable<[Repository]> in
        if query.isEmpty {
            return .just([])
        }
        return searchGitHub(query)
            .catchErrorJustReturn([])
    }
   .bind(to: tableView.rx.items(cellIdentifier: "Cell")) {
        (index, repository: Repository, cell) in
        cell.textLabel?.text = repository.name
        cell.detailTextLabel?.text = repository.url
    }
    .disposed(by: disposeBag)

The goal of this talk will be to introduce reactive programming to fellow developers, explain to them what it can bring them in their daily work, and show them enough example so that they are able to put in it practice, if they wish to.
